To achieve the desired functionality, you'll need a Markdown parser and a way to convert Markdown syntax to HTML tags. Here's a simple implementation using the boost::spirit library for parsing Markdown and HTML escaping:

```cpp
#include <boost/spirit/include/qi.hpp>
#include <boost/fusion/include/adapt_struct.hpp>
#include <string>

namespace md2html {

struct Markdown {
    std::string text;
};

BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT(md2html::Markdown, text)

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    namespace qi = boost::spirit::qi;
    namespace ascii = boost::spirit::ascii;

    Markdown mkd;
    std::string error;

    if (!qi::parse(markdown.begin(), markdown.end(), // Input Iterator
            (*qi::noSkip[ascii::char_ - '\n'])              // Text
            | ("[" >> *(ascii::char_ -"]]") >> "]")           // Image
            | ("``"` >> *(ascii::char_ - "``") >> "```)")     // Code Block
            , mkd.text)) {
        error.assign("Invalid Markdown format");
    }

    std::string html = "";
    html += "<html><body>";
    html += qi::raw[ascii::not_(qi::eoi)][qi::omega[ascii::char_]].name("Text") << "<p>";
    html += qi::raw[ascii::not_(qi::eoi)][ascii::char_].name("Text") << "</p>";
    html += "</body></html>";

    return html;
}
}
```

In this code, we create a `Markdown` struct and use boost::spirit to parse Markdown text. The rules for parsing are:

* `*qi::noSkip[ascii::char_ - '\n']`: Text
* `["[" >> *(ascii::char_ -"]]") >> "]"`: Image (e.g., `[Image description](https://example.com/image.jpg)`)
* `"``"` >> *(ascii::char_ - "``") >> "```)`: Code Block (e.g., ``code``)

If the Markdown text is invalid, an error message is returned.

For converting Markdown to HTML, a simple rule-based approach is taken:

* `qi::raw[ascii::not_(qi::eoi)][ascii::char_]`: Text will be wrapped in `<p>` tags

The `markdownToHtml` function takes a Markdown string, parses it, and returns the corresponding HTML code.

Note that this is a very basic implementation and doesn't cover all Markdown features, such as headers, bold text, links, etc. For a full Markdown parser, consider using a dedicated library like `dox` or `commonmarkcpp`.

Also, consider escaping HTML entities in the Markdown text to avoid security issues. In a real-world application, you'd want to sanitize the input Markdown before parsing it.

