Here is an example of how a table of contents (TOC) can be generated automatically in a LATEX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
Text for introduction...

\subsection{Background}
Text for background...

\section{Methods}
Text for methods...

\section*{References}
Text for references...

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the table of contents. The TOC is automatically generated by LATEX based on the section headings (`\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) in the document. The `*` symbol after `\section` is used to indicate that this section should not be numbered in the TOC.

If you want to customize the appearance of the TOC, you can use the `\addcontentsline` command, which adds an entry to the TOC. For example, if you have a section titled "References" and you don't want it to be automatically included in the TOC, you can add the following command before the `\section*{References}`:

```latex
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{References}
```

This command tells LATEX to add an entry for "References" in the TOC, even though it's not a numbered section.

You can also customize the TOC by changing the font, spacing, and alignment using the `\section` command options, such as `\section*[font style]{section title}`.

Note that if you want to include chapters (instead of sections) in the TOC, you need to use a document class that supports chapters, such as `report` or `book`, and replace `\section` with `\chapter`.

